org.fpe4j

Class FFX

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.fpe4j.FFX

  • public class FFX
extends java.lang.Object
    Implementation of the FFX algorithm described in The FFX Mode of Operation for Format-Preserving Encryption, by Mihir Bellare, Phillip Rogaway, and Terence Spies.

    To use this class, you must construct an instance using either of the constructors, then call the encrypt() and/or decrypt() methods. At a minimum, you must supply the split(n), rnds(n) and F(K,n,T,i,B) functions, along with the other FFX parameters.

    The round function F must be constructed from a block cipher or hash function. For AES, the CBC MAC and CMAC modes are recommended. For hash functions, F could be constructed using HMAC.

    At best, FFX is only as secure as the supplied parameter sets. At its worst, FFX may produce output that is less secure than the underlying block cipher or hash function.

    FFX itself, and this implementation in particular, may not be an efficient way to implement a specific FPE function derived from FFX. The generality of FFX precludes some optimizations that may be possible in more direct implementation of a single FPE algorithm.

    Author:
    Kai Johnson

           FFX.FeistelMethod method,
           FFX.SplitFunction split,
           FFX.RoundCounter rnds,
           FFX.RoundFunction F)
        Construct a new FFX instance from explicit parameters.
        Parameters:
        radix - The range of values for symbols in plaintexts and ciphertexts, 0..radix for each symbol.
        minlen - The minimum length of plaintext and ciphertext inputs.
        maxlen - The maximum length of plaintext and ciphertext inputs.
        maxTlen - The maximum length of tweak inputs.
        blockwise - True if the functions for the [+] and [-] operations in the Feistel rounds are blockwise arithmetic, false if the functions use charwise arithmetic
        method - The Feistel method, either ONE where the array is re-partitioned on each round, or TWO where the array partitions are swapped on each round.
        split - Function to determine where to split input arrays.
        rnds - Function to determine the number of Feistel rounds.
        F - Pseudorandom function for Feistel rounds.

      • encrypt

        public int[] encrypt(javax.crypto.SecretKey K,
                     byte[] T,
                     int[] X)
              throws java.security.InvalidKeyException
        FFX.Encrypt(K, T, X) - Encrypts a plaintext string of numerals and produces a ciphertext string of numerals of the same length and radix.

        Parameters:
        K - The 128-, 192- or 256-bit AES key.
        T - The tweak with length in the range [minTlen..maxTlen].
        X - The plaintext numeral string with length in the range [minlen..maxlen] and element values in the range [0..radix].
        Returns:
        The ciphertext numeral string of the same length with element values in the same range.
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - If any of the arguments are null.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - If the length of T is not within the range of [minTlen..maxTlen]; the length of X is not within the range [minlen..maxlen]; radixX.length is less than 100; or any value X[i] is not in the range [0..radix].
        java.security.InvalidKeyException - If K is not a valid key for the underlying cipher.
